Optimize Your Experience Section for Buyers, Not HR
Traditional thinking says the Experience section should list your responsibilities at each job. In B2B sales and marketing, that mindset is outdated.

Your Experience section should tell the story of the results you have delivered, the clients you have served, and the problems you have solved. Each role description is an opportunity to demonstrate your expertise and reinforce your credibility with potential buyers.

Instead of writing: "Managed a team of five sales representatives and oversaw quarterly targets"

Write: "Led a team that generated over 2,000 qualified B2B leads per quarter across healthcare, fintech, and IT security verticals, using a combination of content syndication, account-based marketing, and intent-driven outreach."

See the difference? One tells the reader your function. The other tells the reader your value.

Use metrics wherever possible. Numbers build credibility quickly. They signal that you are results-oriented and that you track what matters.

The Featured Section: Turn Your Profile Into a Portfolio
The Featured section sits prominently near the top of your profile and is one of the most underutilized sections on LinkedIn. It allows you to pin posts, articles, links, documents, and media that showcase your expertise.

Think of it as your professional highlight reel. In B2B, this is where you can display:

Thought leadership articles you have written or been featured in. Case studies that demonstrate results for clients. Free resources like whitepapers, guides, or media kits that offer immediate value. Webinar recordings or speaking engagements. Testimonials or recommendations from clients and partners.

The goal is to give any visitor immediate proof of your expertise without requiring them to scroll through your entire activity feed. The Featured section lets you control the narrative about who you are and what you deliver.

Build Credibility Through Recommendations and Skills
Recommendations are social proof in its most powerful form on LinkedIn. A written recommendation from a client, partner, or colleague carries far more weight than any self-description you could write about yourself.

In 2026, B2B buyers are sophisticated. They research vendors thoroughly before initiating a conversation. A profile with five to ten strong recommendations from recognizable professionals in relevant industries immediately communicates trustworthiness.

When asking for recommendations, be specific. Ask the recommender to speak to a particular project, outcome, or quality. Generic recommendations that say "John is a great professional" add little value. Specific ones that say "Intent Amplify's team helped us increase our qualified lead volume by 40% in the first quarter" are conversion tools.

Your Skills section also matters for discoverability. LinkedIn's algorithm uses skills to match profiles with relevant searches. Make sure your top three pinned skills are the ones most relevant to your B2B buyers — not the ones you find easiest or most comfortable to list.

